    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-05-26T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-05-26T07:00:00-05:00" n="584"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d584">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.248/218: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Standley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Kuibyshev</hi> (<hi rend="smallcaps"
                            >Moscow</hi>)</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1942-05-26T15:00:00+03:00">May 26, 1942—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 5:05 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>447. Department’s 220, May 1 [<hi rend="italic">11</hi>], 10 [<hi rend="italic"
                        >9</hi>] p.m. In addition to my own personal approach on the subject to
                    Stalin, Molotov, Mikoyan, Vyshinsky and Lozovsky, I have been at pains to have
                    the matter of air routes taken up on every possible opportunity by the Military
                    and Naval Attachés and by General Faymonville. Michela has sent the War
                    Department today a personal message (his No. 93, May 26<note n="92"
                        xml:id="d584fn92">No copy found in Department files.</note>) from me to
                    General Marshall<note n="93" xml:id="d584fn93">Gen. George C. Marshall, Chief of
                        Staff of the United States Army.</note> outlining the efforts made and the
                    difficulties encountered, and informing him that concrete proposals must be
                    offered if Soviet doubts and suspicions are to be overcome.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Standley</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
